                "name": "Kanwalpal Singh Flora",
                "href": "/profile/Kanwalpal-Singh-Flora"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes. One can write in all Indic Indo-Aryan scripts interchangeably. Example, I want to have fun. \u0986\u09ae\u09bf \u09ae\u099c\u09be \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u099a\u09be\u0987 (Ami Maja Korte Chai) Bengali \u0906\u092e\u093f \u092e\u091c\u093e \u0915\u094b\u0930\u0924\u0947 \u091a\u093e\u0908 Hindi in Devanagari. But generally there will be 2 issues, example since Bengali written in Devanagari is not standardized right letter combination may not be used by casual users to make the same sounds. The written language will look odd to both Hindi and Bengali speakers , and may even take longer to read because reading 'patterns' or similar shapes becomes second nature for native readers of their own language. Thanks Aaditya to remind one more thing just see how \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 sounds and in Devanagari to make the same sound additional \u094b is needed. I wrote it in English as i grew up in Bengal still forgot to put it in Devanagari. These are challenges of transliteration. But yes it can be used. ",
